issue_body:
Sorry, please test this program first before close this issue.
No matter the thread use the function 'getm' or not,  If this function was invoked, all threads would be binded on the same core of CPU.  You can move the line: matrix<double, 3, 3> w = getm() * getm(); into body of thread, the result is same. But when using declaration 1, the usage of CUP is normal.
The key problem is not about the body of thread, the body in thread cloud be anything. I think it may be because of memory management of matrix.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
#include < thread>
#include <dlib/matrix.h>

using namespace std;
using namespace dlib;

//const matrix<double, 3, 3> getm() {    // declaration 1
const matrix<double, 3, 0> getm() {      // declaration 2
    return matrix<double, 3, 3>();
}

int main(int argc, char* argv[])
{
    int threads = 4;
    matrix<double, 3, 3> w = getm() * getm();
    std::thread ths[threads];
    for (int i = 0; i < threads; i++) {
        ths[i] = std::thread([]() {
            int a = 1;
            for (;;) {
                a = (a * std::rand() + 1234) % 1000;
            }
        });
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < threads; i++) {
        ths[i].join();
    }
    exit (0);
}
-------------------------------------------------

As declaration 2, the return type is matrix<double, 3, 0>, When this program is running, all threads run on only one core of CPU, in other words, One core is 100% usage, others is free.
As declaration 1, I change the return type to matrix<double, 3, 3>, all cores of CPU is 100% usage, this is my expected result.
I do this test, because this problem exists in shape_predictor.
In function 'find_affine_transform' (geometry/point_transforms.h),
the line: const matrix<double,2,3> m = Q*pinv(P);
The matrix P is defined as matrix<double,3,0>, so return type of template function pinv is matrix<double,3,0>.

* **Version**: 19.9
* **Where did you get dlib**: github
* **Platform**: ubuntu 16.04 64
* **Compiler**: gcc 5.4.0

Windows 7/MingW x64 GCC 5.3
With dnn_mnist_ex.cpp sample, I found that restarting training process does not work correctly - only first saving of state file can be loaded. After first sate file is saved, training process fails to overwrite it with renaming temporary file

While debugging, I found at file https://github.com/davisking/dlib/blob/master/dlib/dnn/trainer.h, line s 705-707:
```c++
    // Now that we know the state is safely saved to disk, delete the old sync
    // file and move the .tmp file to it.
    std::rename(tempfile.c_str(), sync_filename.c_str());
```

The result code of std::rename is not checked. And on Windows it returns -1:
```c++
     int res = std::rename(tempfile.c_str(), sync_filename.c_str());
     if (res)
           perror("Error renaming file");
```

The output is: *Error renaming file: File exists*

This is Windows-specific issue, according to http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/cstdio/rename
>If newname names an existing file, the function may either fail or override the existing file, depending on the specific system and library implementation.


If I remove state file manually wile training process is running - it is saved, but only once until I remove it again

