(To run the example, MENTION full `file://` address of `param.json` in above `swagger.json`)

The issue being dict gets dereferenced twice, once during `from_dict` [init](https://github.com/Yelp/bravado-core/blob/49a322f5aec84f7c50409c136f82888ed96b26f0/bravado_core/spec.py#L88) and later when it calls build, and then [validate_spec](https://github.com/Yelp/swagger_spec_validator/blob/master/swagger_spec_validator/validator20.py#L41).

Note: The error does not occur in all cases, but in some specific cases.

I just ran into an issue when attempting to use `bulk_create` on some models using the `TimeStampedModel` Mixin. This wasn't an issue with previous version of the library. On inspection I observed the following lines

    def save(self, **kwargs):
         self.update_modified = kwargs.pop('update_modified', True)
         super(TimeStampedModel, self).save(**kwargs)

on `django_extensions/db/fields/__init__.py` line 28-31

When a multiple model instances are initialized and are are saved using `Model.object.bulk_create`. An exception is raised. Tracing the exception, I observed this

    def pre_save(self, model_instance, add):
        if not model_instance.update_modified:
            return model_instance.modified
        return super(ModificationDateTimeField, self).pre_save(model_instance, add)

on `django_extensions/db/fields/__init__.py` line 412-415. 
since `model_instance.update_model` is created only when the save function is called, running `bulk_create` before actually saving any of the model instances throws `AttributeError: '***' object has no attribute 'update_modified'`

